runs.response:
When a user exceeds their query limit the API returns a 429 (Too Many Requests) error and includes rate-limit details in the response and headers.

Common responses:

- Monthly-query limit example:
{
  "success": false,
  "error": "Monthly query limit exceeded",
  "usage": {
    "current": 101,
    "max": 100,
    "exceeded": true,
    "reset_at": "2026-02-01T00:00:00Z"
  }
}

- Per-minute limit example:
{
  "error": {
    "code": "RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED",
    "message": "Rate limit exceeded. Try again in 60 seconds"
  }
}

Rate-limit headers are also included in every response:
X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset (seconds until reset).

(You may also see an INSUFFICIENT_CREDITS error when lacking monthly credits on certain plans.)

When a user exceeds their query limit the API rejects further requests and returns a 429 (Too Many Requests) response with rate‑limit details. For monthly limits you typically get a response like:

{
  "success": false,
  "error": "Monthly query limit exceeded",
  "usage": {
    "current": 101,
    "max": 100,
    "exceeded": true,
    "reset_at": "2026-02-01T00:00:00Z"
  }
}

Responses also include rate‑limit headers (X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset). Some endpoints may instead return an error object such as:

{
  "error": {
    "code": "RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED",
    "message": "Rate limit exceeded. Try again in 60 seconds"
  }
}

or an INS UFFICIENT_CREDITS error for credit-based limits. The client should back off and retry after the indicated reset time.
